    h2.
      Essential features #[br.hide--desktop]of binge eating disorder (BED)

    //-p.sub-head.
      In order to be diagnosed with BED, an individual must meet all #[br.hide--mobile]of the following #[em DSM-5]#[sup ®] diagnostic criteria.#[sup 1]
    
    p.sub-head.
      In order to receive a diagnosis of BED, an individual must meet #[br.hide--mobile]the #[em DSM-5]#[sup ®] diagnostic criteria listed below#[sup 1]:


    ol.number
      li
        | Recurring episodes of binge eating are characterized #[br.hide--mobile]by the following:

        //-| Recurrent episodes of binge eating. An episode of #[br.hide--mobile]binge eating is characterized by #[em both] of the following:
        ul.bullet
          li.
            Consuming an abnormally large amount of food #[br.hide--mobile]in a short period of time (eg, within 2 hours), #[br.hide--mobile]compared to what others might eat in the same #[br.hide--mobile]amount of time; and
          //-li.
            Eating, in a discrete period of time (eg, within any #[br.hide--mobile]2-hour period), an amount of food that is definitely #[br.hide--mobile]larger than what most people would eat in a similar #[br.hide--mobile]period of time under similar circumstances. 
          li.
            Experiencing a lack of control over eating during #[br.hide--mobile]an episode (eg, an inability to stop eating)
          //-li.
            A sense of lack of control over eating during the #[br.hide--mobile]episode (eg, a feeling that one cannot stop eating or #[br.hide--mobile]control what or how much one is eating). 
      li
        | Binge eating episodes exhibit at least 3 of the #[br.hide--mobile]following characteristics:
        //-| The binge eating episodes are associated with #[em 3 #[br.hide--mobile](or more)] of the following:
        ul.bullet
          li.
            Consuming food faster than normal;
          //-li.
            Eating much more rapidly than normal.
          li.
            Consuming food until uncomfortably full;
          //-li.
            Eating until feeling uncomfortably full.
          li.
            Consuming large amounts of food when not hungry;
          //-li.
            Eating large amounts of food when not feeling physically hungry.
          li.
            Consuming food alone due to embarrassment; and
          //-li.
            Eating alone because of feeling embarrassed by how much one is eating.
          li.
            Feeling disgusted, depressed, or guilty after eating a large amount #[br.hide--desktop]of food
          //-li.
            Feeling disgusted with oneself, depressed, or very guilty afterward.
      li.
        Significant distress regarding #[br.hide--desktop]binge eating.
      li.
        Binge eating occurs at least once weekly for 3 months, on average.
      li.
        Compensatory behaviors are not observed like those associated with bulimia #[br.hide--mobile]nervosa, and the binge eating does not occur during an episode of bulimia nervosa #[br.hide--mobile]or anorexia nervosa.
      //-li.
        Not associated with the recurrent use of inappropriate compensatory behavior #[br.hide--mobile]as in bulimia nervosa and does not occur exclusively during the course of bulimia nervosa #[br.hide--mobile]or anorexia nervosa.

